node.text:
Celebrate with @unworldoceansday and @oceanic.global starting today at 10 am EST. 
When the world feels like
it’s at a standstill, it’s important to remember what keeps it spinning. Our ocean is our life source, supporting us & every other organism on earth. Celebrate @UNWorldOceansDay
on June 8th with @UnitedNations
and @Oceanic.Global
to learn what thought leaders around the world are doing to protect the ocean and how you can be part of the solution. Featured ocean voices include @caradelevingne,
@fatoumata_diawara__, @fcousteau, @c.syresmith, @jackharries, @thegreatbubblebarrier, @codysimpson, @oceanx, @alessandraambrosio and
more! 
This all-digital event is
free and open to all online. Learn more & register:  UNWorldOceansDay.org/2020

Coming up for fresh air 🐢⁣ Captured by @thephilwaller these may just be the best turtle headshots we've ever seen 🥰 Tag someone who has to see this!

This is a Green Sea Turtle, named for the green colour of the far under its shell, nothing to do with their outside⁣⁣.

Fun fact: "Turtles can hold their breath up to 30 minutes. @thephilwaller caught this guy getting in a last breath just before the sun set 🌅🐢"
#sea #turtle

Belugas whales can be found in wild habitats all around the Arctic from Canada and Greenland to Norway, Russia and Alaska. They are cultural animals who generation after generation, pass social learning on to their young.

node.text:
We humans have successfully photographed a black hole, landed rovers on Mars, and sent spacecraft to the dark side of the moon. However, our very own planet remains one of the last unknown frontiers. 

The ocean is the lifeblood of Earth, covering over 70 percent of the planet’s surface, driving weather, regulating temperature, and ultimately supporting life. Throughout history, the ocean has been a vital source of transport, commerce, growth, and inspiration.

But more than 80% of the ocean remains unexplored.

During one of his dive, underwater photographer @gutsytuason had a rare opportunity to shoot a larval Wunderpus octopus. 

The incredible image highlight just how delicate this creature is; the baby’s transparent body allows an observer to even see its brain. 

However, little is known of its life history and behavior, as the species was discovered in the 1980s and only officially described in 2006. 

📷: @gutsytuason
#DiscoverOcean

node.text:
Moray eels 🖐
Fun fact: 
- A moray eel appears dangerous because it continually exposes its mouth and teeth. This action, however, is not a hostile gesture, but simply the way an eel breathes. Morays have large mouths and powerful jaws with a vice-like grip. Most species have sharp, thin teeth that protrude from the upper and lower jaws, and sometimes from the roof of the mouth. The teeth point backwards to prevent slippery prey from escaping. 
- Because most moray eels have low dorsal (top) fins and lack pectoral and pelvic fins, they do not have a great amount of lateral stability. It is not uncommon to see moray eels lying or drifting on their sides or even upside down.
📸 @espekanela
#DiscoverOcean #underwater #animals

node.text:
Cymothoa Exigua

AKA the tongue eating louse

The better half (females) of these parasitic isopods enter the host fish through the gills and zero in on the tongue.

Using its front claws, it proceeds to sever the blood vessels in the tongue and suck all the blood out, causing it to atrophy and fall away.

The parasite then replaces the fish's tongue by attaching its own body to the muscles of the tongue stub.

This is the only known case of a parasite functionally replacing a host organ.

Once the tongue has been replaced, cymothoa exigua feeds on both the blood and mucus of the fish, along with any nutrients they can scrape away for themself when the fish eats.

When it's time to reproduce, males will simply climb inside the hosts mouth and mate with the female while shes still attached.

She stays there indefinitely. Even while giving birth to a whole brood of young, she does so inside the fish's mouth.

If the host fish dies, the parasite detaches itself from the tongue stub.

It is not fully known what happens to the parasite once they leave a dead host.
Via @natureismetal
#DiscoverOcean

node.text:
Mini Godzilla!
Marine iguanas are the only lizards on Earth that spends time in the ocean. They live only on the Galapagos Islands, and like many Galapagos species, they have adapted to an island lifestyle. Populations across the archipelago have been isolated from each other for so long that each island has its own subspecies.

Marine iguanas are most noted for their ability to feed in shallow, marine waters. They are herbivores and eat marine algae growing along rocky shores and underwater. In the water, they swim with a snake-like motion and hold themselves against the bottom with their long claws in order to graze. Though they feed in the water, marine iguanas are predominately terrestrial. They are often observed warming themselves in the sun, and they nest along the shore. 
Marine iguanas are also known for their very efficient salt glands, where they “sneeze” out salt. Because they feed underwater, they ingest a large amount of saltwater. In order to prevent dehydration, they must expel salt without expelling water, so they have specialized glands that remove salt from their blood. They also have the incredible ability to shrink. In times of reduced food availability – particularly during El Niño climate events – they may shrink by as much as 20%. The now smaller individuals require less food. Once their preferred algae return to high levels, they quickly regain the lost size. .
